-- FTSE MIB Stock Index Is Little Changed; Beni Stabili, Exor, Indesit Move
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-12-22T16:41:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-22/fiat-indesit-sias-tenaris-ubi-shares-may-move-italian-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
ended little changed, losing 3.23 points to 20,733.37 at the
5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) dropped 2.1 percent to 3.55
euros, after rising 9.4 percent in two days. Shares of the
lender failed to close above their 50-day moving average for a
second day.  Beni Stabili SpA  (BNS IM) dropped 2.3 percent to 64.5 euro
cents, the lowest this month. Mediobanca SpA placed 81,739,700
shares in Beni Stabili at 63 euro cents each. The stake
represents 4.3 percent of Beni Stabili’s capital.  Exor SpA  (EXO IM) advanced for a third day, rising 3.8
percent to 24.91 euros. CA Cheuvreux lifted its price estimate
on Fiat’s main shareholder to 27.5 euros from 23 euros and
reiterated an “outperform” rating, citing “good financial
flexibility” and “room for dividends/buybacks.”  Fiat SpA  (F IM) increased 1.3 percent to 15.31 euros, the
highest since May 2008. Fidentiis Equities SV SA, which has a
“buy” rating on the carmaker, said in a note that “M&A is
still the main catalyst, in our view more likely for the auto
rather than for the industrial division.”  Equita Sim SpA said in a note that “both the entities
involved are appealing.” Equita also kept a “buy” rating.  Fondiaria-Sai SpA  (FSA IM) rose 1.9 percent to 6.39 euros,
gaining for a third day. Mediobanca Securities, which has a
“neutral” rating on Italy’s second-biggest insurer, said in a
note that yesterday’s announcement of a shareholders’ meeting in
January to review a proposed capital increase was positive.  Indesit Company SpA  (IND IM) gained 2.7 percent to 8.48
euros, the steepest increase in three weeks. The company will
invest 70 million euros on new products in 2011 to boost its
presence in high-end appliances, Chief Executive Officer Marco
Milani told daily Il Sole 24 Ore.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net  